│ I have failed to solve this issue multiple times due to what I believe are environmental problems with applying patches. I will make one final, good-faith attempt.                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ My analysis of the bug remains that there is state corruption between the loop peeling and loop unrolling phases. The `LastValueMap`, which maps original values to their last-cloned    │
│ versions, is populated with values from the peeled iteration. This map is then incorrectly used by the first iteration of the main unrolling loop, causing an incorrect value to be      │
│ propagated to an exit PHI.                                                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The most direct fix is to clear `LastValueMap` after peeling is done and before the main unrolling loop begins. My previous attempts to insert `LastValueMap.clear();` at the correct    │
│ location (which I've identified as line 713 in `LoopUnroll.cpp`) failed due to file corruption.                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This time, I will manually reconstruct the file to perform the insertion, avoiding the problematic `sed -i` and `patch` commands. I will use a command block that prints the first part  │
│ of the file, then prints my line of code, then prints the rest of the file, redirecting the whole stream into a new file which then replaces the original. This is the most careful and  │
│ explicit way to perform the edit and should prevent any syntax corruption.                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ { sed -n '1,712p' /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopUnroll.cpp; echo '    LastValueMap.clear();'; sed -n '713,$p'                                               │
